Raw dev notes -- SEO Sprint for SmartHebrewRTL Landing Page

Okay, so this past week or so has been all about getting the landing page for my SmartHebrewRTL extension out there and discoverable. For anyone who doesn't know, this extension is a passion project of mine – it's designed to fix the often-broken display of Hebrew text on the web, especially in tricky places like streaming video subtitles or sites that just don't handle Right-to-Left languages well. The landing page is crucial because it's where people learn what it does and how to get it.

This period was a full-on SEO sprint. I started by adding the actual Hebrew name of the extension to the meta tags, along with a bunch of relevant keywords. It felt important to have the native name there for search engines. I also linked to the project's blog, which hopefully helps with content and authority. A slightly more advanced step was implementing JSON-LD for `alternateName` – that felt like I was finally doing some proper structured data work. On the more mundane but equally important side, I added my email to the footer, because people need a way to contact me, right?

Then came the big SEO push: setting up the canonical URL (so Google knows which version of the page is the 'real' one), creating a `robots.txt` file to guide crawlers, and generating a `sitemap.xml`. These are foundational but easy to mess up, so I spent extra time double-checking them. I also uploaded the Google Search Console verification file, which is like telling Google, "Hey, this is my site, please pay attention to it!"

Finally, I updated the version number on the page to 2.2.0. This was a good opportunity to refine the messaging, and I added a new tagline: "flicker-free streaming." This really highlights one of the core problems the extension solves – not just displaying Hebrew, but displaying it *smoothly* and *correctly* without those annoying flickers or broken characters you often see in video players. It felt good to distill that into something punchy. And, of course, a copyright notice in the footer, because professionalism.

Honestly, SEO feels like a bit of a black box sometimes. You put all these tags and files in place, and you just have to trust that the search engines will eventually pick it up and rank you. It's not as immediately gratifying as fixing a bug or building a new feature where you see instant results. But it's absolutely essential. It was a good reminder that a great product needs to be discoverable, and that means doing the "invisible" work of making sure search engines understand what your site is about. I'm learning to appreciate this aspect of development more – it's not just about the code, but about the entire ecosystem around the product. It felt like a big step towards making the extension truly accessible to its target audience.

Next up: Monitor Search Console and analytics to see if these changes are making a difference.
